  "prompt": "Why does blue vitriol change its colour from blue to white on heating?",
  "response": "Blue vitriol, chemically known as copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate (CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O), is a bright blue crystalline substance that contains water molecules in its structure. When heated, the water of crystallization is removed, leading to a process called dehydration.\n\nUpon heating, copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate loses its water molecules and transforms into anhydrous copper(II) sulfate (CuSO\u2084), which is a white powder. The color change from blue to white is due to the loss of the coordinated water molecules that are part of the hydrated crystal structure. The presence of water in the hydrated form is responsible for the blue color, while the anhydrous form lacks these water molecules and appears white.\n\nThe chemical reaction can be summarized as follows:\n\nCuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O (blue) \u2192 CuSO\u2084 (white) + 5 H\u2082O (water vapor)\n\nThis transformation is an example of how hydration states in certain compounds can significantly influence their physical appearance and properties.",
